post_text:
A message from our Superintendent
Re: Reopening of Schools

The Newfound Schools Administrative Team is working diligently to develop a plan to safely reopen our schools. Committee work is being done by our Administrators, Administrative Assistants, School Nurses, Facilities Director, Technology Director and Teachers.

Our work includes developing plans for Technology, Health Management, Social Emotional Learning, Teaching and Learning, Special Education, Logistics, Professional Development and Facilities.

Through the work of these committees we are confident that we will be prepared to open schools safely.

We are planning to present our reopening plan to the NASD school board on August 3rd. The plan will be distributed to all stakeholders after the school board meeting.

post_text: Jenne and Matt from the Forest Service Dept in the White Mountain National Forest visited Mrs. Carter's First Grade class. They shared a story about animals in winter and talked about the subnivean zone, the layer under the snow where animals live. They also shared several pelts of animals in New Hampshire that the students passed around. They finished the visit by sharing skull models. The students were very excited to have this opportunity! Thank you for such a great experience!

post_text: Mrs. Caristi's reading group read a story about a tortilla factory. After reading the story, they went to visit Cielito restaurant in Bristol to learn more about tortillas. Cielito was absolutely amazing in explaining the different types of tortillas, explaining how they use them, and allowing each student to touch the different tortillas. The students then enjoyed a lunch including tortillas. THANK YOU very much Cielito for giving our BES students such a wonderful connection to what they read!

post_text: For Mrs. Jackson's third graders, the last activity in their weather unit was to design a paper house that would not blow away in a windstorm. They had to build the house and then use certain materials to modify it to withstand wind from a paper fan. The roof had to stay on and the house stay in place. The students had great conversations and revisions to their projects...what a great science week of engineering!!

post_text: Mrs. Symonds' Third Grade class has been working on Life Cycles. They have 1,000 Red Wiggler Worms that are composting food scraps and producing waste, which is like gold for gardens! The rich hummus (castings) will be harvested and used as nourishment for the plants they are growing in their classroom greenhouse!
